SIMPLE: produce
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Produce
<hw>Pro*duce"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Produced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Producing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>producere</ets>, <ets>productum</ets>, to bring forward, beget,
produce; <ets>pro</ets> forward, forth + <ets>ducere</ets> to lead. See
<er>Duke</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To bring forward; to lead forth; to offer to view or
notice; to exhibit; to show; <as>as, to <ex>produce</ex> a witness or
evidence in court</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Produce</qex> your cause, saith the Lord.</q> <rj><qau>Isa.
xli. 21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your parents did not <qex>produce</qex> you much into the
world.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To bring forth, as young, or as a natural product or
growth; to give birth to; to bear; to generate; to propagate; to yield;
to furnish; <as>as, the earth <ex>produces</ex> grass; trees
<ex>produce</ex> fruit; the clouds <ex>produce</ex> rain.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This soil <qex>produces</qex> all sorts of palm trees.</q>
<rj><qau>Sandys.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[They] <qex>produce</qex> prodigious births of body or mind.</q>
<rj><qau> Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The greatest jurist his country had <qex>produced</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to be or to happen; to originate, as an
effect or result; to bring about; <as>as, disease <ex>produces</ex>
pain; vice <ex>produces</ex> misery.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To give being or form to; to manufacture; to make;
<as>as, a manufacturer <ex>produces</ex> excellent wares</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To yield or furnish; to gain; <as>as, money at
interest <ex>produces</ex> an income; capital <ex>produces</ex>
profit.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To draw out; to extend; to lengthen; to prolong;
<as>as, to <ex>produce</ex> a man's life to threescore</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>To extend; -- applied to a line,
surface, or solid; <as>as, to <ex>produce</ex> a side of a
triangle</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Produce</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Produce
<hw>Pro*duce"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To yield or furnish
appropriate offspring, crops, effects, consequences, or
results.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Produce</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Produce
<hw>Prod"uce</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>That which is
produced, brought forth, or yielded; product; yield; proceeds; result of
labor, especially of agricultural labors</def>; hence, specifically,
<def>agricultural products.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Producement</ent>⟦br⟧
